{"title_page": "Rough sex murder defense", "text_new": "'''Rough sex murder defense''', also known as the '''50 Shades defense''' (after ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey]]''), is employed by some people accused of [[intimate partner violence|murdering their sexual partner]], who claim that the death occurred because of injuries sustained during [[consensual sex]].<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=independent>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sophie |title=If the government bans the \u2018rough sex\u2019 defence, what would it mean? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/women/rough-sex-defence-ban-domestic-abuse-bill-government-2020-a9374386.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=4 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Urwin |first1=Shanti Das and Rosamund |title=Killers go free thanks to \u2018Fifty Shades\u2019 defence |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/killers-go-free-thanks-to-fifty-shades-defence-6l9s5976q |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=24 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1988, it was reported that the rough sex defense was becoming more popular among men suspected of murdering their female partners because of the 1986 \"[[Robert Chambers (criminal)|preppy murder]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Acland |first1=Charles R. |title=Youth, Murder, Spectacle: The Cultural Politics Of \"\"Youth In Crisis\"\" |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-97146-4 |page=66 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8wHFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&lpg=PA66&dq=rough+sex+murder&source=bl&ots=ofUynfcOcZ&sig=ACfU3U0OCy8hqVsyaVIX3r8TLbVodejkLw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi_wsyryOnoAhWLtJ4KHbsKAjI4KBDoATADegQIDBAt#v=onepage&q=rough%20sex%20murder&f=false |language=en}}</ref> In 1989, American jurist George Buzash recommended a \"[[strict liability]] approach to 'rough sex' homicides\" in order to prevent defendants from claiming the rough sex defense; he felt that it rewarded [[perjury]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Buzash |first1=George E. |title=The Rough Sex Defense |journal=[[The Journal of Criminal Law & Criminology]] |volume=80 |issue=2 |pages=557\u2013584 |url=https://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=6628&context=jclc|date=1989}}</ref> The earliest known use of the defense in the UK was after the death of Carole Califano in 1972; her abusive partner was able to get the criminal charge reduced to [[manslaughter]].<ref name=\"independent\" /> At least sixty defendants in the UK have used the defence as of 2020, and forty-five percent were able to avoid conviction for murder.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> According to experts, use of the defense has risen in the last few decades.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=cut>{{cite news |last1=Lampen |first1=Claire |title=The Disturbing Rise of the \u201850 Shades\u2019 Defense for Murder |url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/02/50-shades-of-gray-murder-defense-blames-women-for-rough-sex.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Cut |date=23 February 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nRecently, the defense has been brought to attention by cases such as the [[killing of Cindy Gladue]] in Canada in 2011,<ref name=CNN>{{cite news |last1=Woodyatt |first1=Amy |title=The rise of the '50 Shades' defense in murder trials |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/21/world/grace-millane-sex-game-gone-wrong-intl-gbr/index.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref> the Natalie Connolly case in the United Kingdom in 2018,<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and the [[murder of Grace Millane]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Norris |first1=Sian |title=\u2018Rough sex\u2019 as a defence for murder is grotesque victim-blaming|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/feb/24/rough-sex-defence-murder-grace-millane |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>  New Zealand Detective Inspector Scott Beard said that he opposes the defense: \"I don't believe that rough sex should be a defence ... If people are going to use that as a defence, all it's going to do is revictimise the victim and their family.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leask |first1=Anna |title=Grace Millane murder: Top cop slams 'rough sex' defence - 'it doesn't sit well with me' |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12310555 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=NZ Herald |date=20 February 2020 |language=en-NZ}}</ref>\n\n==Legislative proposals==\nSome campaigners, such as We Can't Consent to This<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and [[Toni Van Pelt]] of the [[National Organization for Women]],<ref name=\"cut\" />  consider the defense a form of [[victim blaming]] and advocate for it to be banned.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |last1=Lowbridge |first1=Caroline |title=Why campaigners want 'rough sex' murder defence ban |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-51151182 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are plans to prevent the rough sex murder defense in the United Kingdom's [[Domestic Abuse Bill 2019]], which was debated before the [[2019 British prorogation controversy|2019 prorogation of parliament]].<ref name=\"independent\" /> Labour MP [[Harriet Harman]] and Conservative MP [[Mark Garnier]] are advocates of the bill; Harman believes that men should be prosecuted for murder even if they did not intend to kill their partner. [[Boris Johnson]], prime minister of the United Kingdom, said \"I agree with Harriet Harman that the '50 Shades defence' is unacceptable and we'll make sure the law is clear on this.\"<ref name=\"BBC\" /> [[Jeremy Corbyn]], former leader of the Labour party, said that he would re-introduce the legislation if elected: \"We will make sure that the \u201850 Shades defence\u2019 is banned, including it directly in our bill.\" Former [[Liberal Democrat]] leader [[Jo Swinson]] also said that her party supports a statutory ban on the use of the defense.<ref name=\"ind2\">{{cite news |last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzy |title=Corbyn, Swinson and Johnson back new laws to combat rising 'rough sex defence' used by killers |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/general-election-rough-sex-defence-deaths-grace-millane-natalie-connolly-a9240976.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=10 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> One precedent for the law is ''[[R v Brown]]'', a case which determined that a victim cannot consent to [[actual bodily harm]].<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Intimate partner violence]]\n[[Category:Homicide]]\n[[Category:Criminal defenses]]\n", "text_old": "'''Rough sex murder defense''', also known as the '''50 Shades defense''' (after [[50 Shades of Gray]]), is employed by some people accused of [[intimate partner violence|murdering their sexual partner]], who claim that the death occurred because of injuries sustained during [[consensual sex]].<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=independent>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sophie |title=If the government bans the \u2018rough sex\u2019 defence, what would it mean? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/women/rough-sex-defence-ban-domestic-abuse-bill-government-2020-a9374386.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=4 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Urwin |first1=Shanti Das and Rosamund |title=Killers go free thanks to \u2018Fifty Shades\u2019 defence |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/killers-go-free-thanks-to-fifty-shades-defence-6l9s5976q |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=24 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1988, it was reported that the rough sex defense was becoming more popular among men suspected of murdering their female partners because of the 1986 \"[[Robert Chambers (criminal)|preppy murder]]\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Acland |first1=Charles R. |title=Youth, Murder, Spectacle: The Cultural Politics Of \"\"Youth In Crisis\"\" |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-97146-4 |page=66 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8wHFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&lpg=PA66&dq=rough+sex+murder&source=bl&ots=ofUynfcOcZ&sig=ACfU3U0OCy8hqVsyaVIX3r8TLbVodejkLw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi_wsyryOnoAhWLtJ4KHbsKAjI4KBDoATADegQIDBAt#v=onepage&q=rough%20sex%20murder&f=false |language=en}}</ref> In 1989, American jurist George Buzash recommended a \"[[strict liability]] approach to 'rough sex' homicides\" in order to prevent defendants from claiming the rough sex defense; he felt that it rewarded [[perjury]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Buzash |first1=George E. |title=The Rough Sex Defense |journal=[[The Journal of Criminal Law & Criminology]] |volume=80 |issue=2 |pages=557\u2013584 |url=https://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=6628&context=jclc|date=1989}}</ref> The earliest known use of the defense in the UK was after the death of Carole Califano in 1972; her abusive partner was able to get the criminal charge reduced to [[manslaughter]].<ref name=\"independent\" /> At least sixty defendants in the UK have used the defence as of 2020, and forty-five percent were able to avoid conviction for murder.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> According to experts, use of the defense has risen in the last few decades.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=cut>{{cite news |last1=Lampen |first1=Claire |title=The Disturbing Rise of the \u201850 Shades\u2019 Defense for Murder |url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/02/50-shades-of-gray-murder-defense-blames-women-for-rough-sex.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Cut |date=23 February 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nRecently, the defense has been brought to attention by cases such as the [[killing of Cindy Gladue]] in Canada in 2011,<ref name=CNN>{{cite news |last1=Woodyatt |first1=Amy |title=The rise of the '50 Shades' defense in murder trials |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/21/world/grace-millane-sex-game-gone-wrong-intl-gbr/index.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref> the Natalie Connolly case in the United Kingdom in 2018,<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and the [[murder of Grace Millane]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Norris |first1=Sian |title=\u2018Rough sex\u2019 as a defence for murder is grotesque victim-blaming|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/feb/24/rough-sex-defence-murder-grace-millane |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>  New Zealand Detective Inspector Scott Beard said that he opposes the defense: \"I don't believe that rough sex should be a defence ... If people are going to use that as a defence, all it's going to do is revictimise the victim and their family.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leask |first1=Anna |title=Grace Millane murder: Top cop slams 'rough sex' defence - 'it doesn't sit well with me' |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12310555 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=NZ Herald |date=20 February 2020 |language=en-NZ}}</ref>\n\n==Legislative proposals==\nSome campaigners, such as We Can't Consent to This<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and [[Toni Van Pelt]] of the [[National Organization for Women]],<ref name=\"cut\" />  consider the defense a form of [[victim blaming]] and advocate for it to be banned.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |last1=Lowbridge |first1=Caroline |title=Why campaigners want 'rough sex' murder defence ban |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-51151182 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are plans to prevent the rough sex murder defense in the United Kingdom's [[Domestic Abuse Bill 2019]], which was debated before the [[2019 British prorogation controversy|2019 prorogation of parliament]].<ref name=\"independent\" /> Labour MP [[Harriet Harman]] and Conservative MP [[Mark Garnier]] are advocates of the bill; Harman believes that men should be prosecuted for murder even if they did not intend to kill their partner. [[Boris Johnson]], prime minister of the United Kingdom, said \"I agree with Harriet Harman that the '50 Shades defence' is unacceptable and we'll make sure the law is clear on this.\"<ref name=\"BBC\" /> [[Jeremy Corbyn]], former leader of the Labour party, said that he would re-introduce the legislation if elected: \"We will make sure that the \u201850 Shades defence\u2019 is banned, including it directly in our bill.\" Former [[Liberal Democrat]] leader [[Jo Swinson]] also said that her party supports a statutory ban on the use of the defense.<ref name=\"ind2\">{{cite news |last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzy |title=Corbyn, Swinson and Johnson back new laws to combat rising 'rough sex defence' used by killers |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/general-election-rough-sex-defence-deaths-grace-millane-natalie-connolly-a9240976.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=10 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> One precedent for the law is ''[[R v Brown]]'', a case which determined that a victim cannot consent to [[actual bodily harm]].<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Intimate partner violence]]\n[[Category:Homicide]]\n[[Category:Criminal defenses]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correct title, italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rough_sex_murder_defense"}
{"title_page": "Vic Watson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name             = Vic Watson\n| image            = Vic Watson.jpg\n| image_size       = 250\n| fullname         = Victor Martin Watson\n| height           =  \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1897|11|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Girton, Cambridgeshire]], England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1988|8|3|1897|11|10|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Girton, Cambridgeshire]], England\n| position         = [[Centre forward]]\n| youthyears1      = \n| youthclubs1      = \n| years1           = 19??\u20131920 \n| clubs1           = [[Wellingborough Town F.C.|Wellingborough Town]] \n| caps1            =\n| goals1           = \n| years2           = 1920\u20131935 \n| clubs2           = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]<ref name =\"whstats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=673&united=Victor_Watson|title=Vic Watson: West Ham Statistics}}</ref> \n| caps2            = 462 \n| goals2           = 298\n| years3           = 1935\u20131936\n| clubs3           = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n| caps3            = 36 \n| goals3           = 14\n| nationalyears1   = 1923\u20131930\n| nationalteam1    = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1    = 5\n| nationalgoals1   = 4\n}}\n\n'''Victor Martin Watson''' (10 November 1897 \u2013 3 August 1988) was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played most of his club football for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].\n\nWatson, a centre forward, played 505 times for West Ham between 1920 and 1936. The club paid just \u00a350 for Vic from Wellingborough, bringing him in to provide cover for [[Syd Puddefoot]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Hogg |first=Tony |title=Who's Who of West Ham United |year=2005 |publisher=Profile Sports Media| isbn= 1-903135-50-8 |page=211}}</ref>\n\nWatson is the club's [[West Ham United F.C. goal records|record goalscorer]] with 326 goals with 298 league and 28 FA cup. 203 of his league goals were from 295 top flight appearances.<ref name =\"whstats\"/> He once scored six, in an 8\u20132 home win against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] on 9 February 1929, scored four goals on three occasions, and managed 13 [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]]s while at West Ham.<ref>{{cite web|title=As Wayne Rooney breaks Sir Bobby Charlton's Man Utd haul, who is your Premier League club's all-time leading goalscorer?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/0/every-premier-league-clubs-all-time-leading-goalscorer/vic-watson7/|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=26 January 2017|date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nWatson gained two international [[Cap (sport)|caps]] with [[England national football team|England]] in 1923 and a further three caps in 1930, scoring four goals in total, including two against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in the [[1930 British Home Championship]].\n\nHe spent one season (1935\u201336) with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] before retiring and he was the club's [[Southampton F.C. seasons|top scorer]] with 14 goals in 36 league appearances.\n\nUpon retiring, he became a market gardener in [[Girton, Cambridgeshire]]. He died in August 1988 at the age of 90.\n\nIn June 2010 a plaque honouring Watson was unveiled in Girton.<ref name=Plaque>{{cite news|last=Grove|first=Jack|title=Residents' campaign for a tribute to local footie hero|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge/Residents-campaign-for-a-tribute-to-local-footie-hero.htm?ID=463427|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130420002301/http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge/Residents-campaign-for-a-tribute-to-local-footie-hero.htm?ID=463427|url-status=dead|archivedate=20 April 2013|accessdate=19 June 2012|newspaper=www.cambridge-news.co.uk|date=13 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''West Ham United'''\n* [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] Runners Up: [[1922-23 in English football|1922\u201323]]\n* [[FA Cup]] finalist: [[FA Cup Final 1923|1923]]\n\n'''England'''\n*[[British Home Championship]]: [[1930 British Home Championship|1930]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061113214816/http://www.englandfc.com/Profiles/php/PlayerProfileByName.php?id=1030 Victor Watson profile] at englandfc.com\n*[http://www.spartacus-educational.com/WHwatsonV.htm Vic Watson photos]\n*[http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=673&united=Victor_Watson West Ham statistics]\n\n{{English First Division/Premier League top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watson, Vic}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Girton, Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:First Division/Premier League top scorers]]\n[[Category:Wellingborough Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name             = Vic Watson\n| image            = Vic Watson.jpg\n| image_size       = 250\n| fullname         = Victor Martin Watson\n| height           =  \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1897|11|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Girton, Cambridgeshire]], England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1988|8|3|1897|11|10|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Girton, Cambridgeshire]], England\n| position         = [[Centre forward]]\n| youthyears1      = \n| youthclubs1      = \n| years1           = 19??\u20131920 \n| clubs1           = [[Wellingborough Town F.C.|Wellingborough Town]] \n| caps1            =\n| goals1           = \n| years2           = 1920\u20131935 \n| clubs2           = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]<ref name =\"whstats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=673&united=Victor_Watson|title=Vic Watson: West Ham Statistics}}</ref> \n| caps2            = 462 \n| goals2           = 298\n| years3           = 1935\u20131936\n| clubs3           = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n| caps3            = 36 \n| goals3           = 14\n| nationalyears1   = 1923\u20131930\n| nationalteam1    = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1    = 5\n| nationalgoals1   = 4\n}}\n\n'''Victor Martin Watson''' (10 November 1897 \u2013 3 August 1988) was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played most of his club football for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].\n\nWatson, a centre forward, played 505 times for West Ham between 1920 and 1936. The club paid just \u00a350 for Vic from Wellingborough, bringing him in to provide cover for [[Syd Puddefoot]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Hogg |first=Tony |title=Who's Who of West Ham United |year=2005 |publisher=Profile Sports Media| isbn= 1-903135-50-8 |page=211}}</ref>\n\nWatson is the club's [[West Ham United F.C. goal records|record goalscorer]] with 326 goals with 298 league and 28 FA cup. 203 of his league goals were from 295 top flight appearances.<ref name =\"whstats\"/> He once scored six, in an 8-2 home win against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] on 9 February 1929, scored four goals on three occasions, and managed 13 [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]]s while at West Ham.<ref>{{cite web|title=As Wayne Rooney breaks Sir Bobby Charlton's Man Utd haul, who is your Premier League club's all-time leading goalscorer?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/0/every-premier-league-clubs-all-time-leading-goalscorer/vic-watson7/|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=26 January 2017|date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nWatson gained two international [[Cap (sport)|caps]] with [[England national football team|England]] in 1923 and a further three caps in 1930, scoring four goals in total, including two against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in the [[1930 British Home Championship]].\n\nHe spent one season (1935\u201336) with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] before retiring and he was the club's [[Southampton F.C. seasons|top scorer]] with 14 goals in 36 league appearances.\n\nUpon retiring, he became a market gardener in [[Girton, Cambridgeshire]]. He died in August 1988 at the age of 90.\n\nIn June 2010 a plaque honouring Watson was unveiled in Girton.<ref name=Plaque>{{cite news|last=Grove|first=Jack|title=Residents' campaign for a tribute to local footie hero|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge/Residents-campaign-for-a-tribute-to-local-footie-hero.htm?ID=463427|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130420002301/http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge/Residents-campaign-for-a-tribute-to-local-footie-hero.htm?ID=463427|url-status=dead|archivedate=20 April 2013|accessdate=19 June 2012|newspaper=www.cambridge-news.co.uk|date=13 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''West Ham United'''\n* [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] Runners Up: [[1922-23 in English football|1922\u201323]]\n* [[FA Cup]] finalist: [[FA Cup Final 1923|1923]]\n\n'''England'''\n*[[British Home Championship]]: [[1930 British Home Championship|1930]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061113214816/http://www.englandfc.com/Profiles/php/PlayerProfileByName.php?id=1030 Victor Watson profile] at englandfc.com\n*[http://www.spartacus-educational.com/WHwatsonV.htm Vic Watson photos]\n*[http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=673&united=Victor_Watson West Ham statistics]\n\n{{English First Division/Premier League top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watson, Vic}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Girton, Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]